===1949 Armistice Agreements===
{{main|1949 Armistice Agreements}}
The [[1947–1948 civil war in Mandatory Palestine]] followed by the [[1948 Arab–Israeli War]] all ended with the February–July [[1949 Armistice Agreements]] between [[Israel]] and [[Egypt]], [[Lebanon]], [[Jordan]], and [[Syria]]. Those Arab countries insisted explicitly in the agreement texts that the agreed Armistice Demarcation Lines ('Green Lines') should not be construed as political or territorial boundaries, thus aiming to safeguard the [[Palestinian right of return|right of return of those Palestinians that had fled their homes during the war]], and the illegitimacy of Israel's use or appropriation of abandoned Palestinian property.

After the 1967 [[Six-Day War]], in which Israel had conquered, among more, the Palestinian [[West Bank]] and [[Gaza Strip]] in a pre-emptive surprise-strike against overtly hostile Arab neighbouring countries, top Israeli leaders like Golda Meir, Menachem Begin and Abba Eban have emphasized that returning to the pre-1967 borders would be extremely dangerous for Israel, bordering on "national suicide".

===Geneva, December 1973===
{{main|Geneva Conference (1973)}}
After the ceasefire on 25 October 1973 ending the [[Yom Kippur War]] (surprise attack on Israel on 6 October by Egypt, Syria, Jordan, Iraq assisted by more countries), the U.S. and U.S.S.R. [[Geneva Conference (1973)|gathered the foreign ministers of Israel, Egypt and Jordan in Geneva]] in December 1973 to pursue "peace", firstly disengagement of armed forces, towards fulfilling [[UN 242|UNSC Resolution 242]] dating from 1967 ("…the need to work for a just and lasting peace in the Middle East in which every State in the area can live in security"). Syria had refused to show up because Israel and the US refused to invite the [[PLO]]. The short conference facilitated a reconciliation between Israel, Egypt, and Syria, but achieved nothing for the Palestinians.

===Camp David, 1978===
{{main|Camp David Accords#Framework for Peace in the Middle East}}
A political agreement was signed between Israel and Egypt (notably excluding representatives from the PLO) in 1978, aiming to establish a self-governing authority in the West Bank and Gaza and autonomy for the inhabitants of those lands, as an attempt towards "Peace in the Middle East". "Autonomy" in this case would not mean "self-determination"; Israeli Prime Minister [[Menachem Begin]] specifically insisted that "on no condition will there be a Palestinian state".<ref name=Khalidi,2013>{{cite book|author=Rashid Khalidi|title=Brokers of Deceit: How the US Has Undermined Peace in the Middle East|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Brokers_of_Deceit&pg=PA|year=|publisher=Beacon Press, 2013 |isbn=978-0-8070-4475-9|quote=Even though Yitzhak Rabin was the first Israeli prime minister to accept formally the idea that the Palestinians were a people, he never officially conceded that this people had the right of national self-determination and statehood. These terms consequently occur nowhere in the 1993 agreements. Thus, although they nominally accepted that the Palestinians were a people, the Oslo accords in fact did no more than formally consecrate Begin's scheme: we have seen that the canny Polish-born lawyer understood that the terms he had obdurately insisted on at Camp David in 1978 "'guarantee that under no condition' can a Palestinian state be created".}}</ref><ref name=Filiu2014>{{cite book|author=Jean-Pierre Filiu|title=Gaza: A History - Jean-Pierre Filiu|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Gaza&pg=PA|year=|publisher=Oxford University Press, 2014 |isbn=978-0-19-020189-0}}</ref>

Meanwhile, Egypt's status as the strongest Arab nation capable of challenging Israel militarily meant that its parallel withdrawal from the Arab-Israeli conflict in the [[Egypt–Israel peace treaty]] (March 1979) significantly weakened the collective military and diplomatic power of the other Arab countries. It has been argued that this shift essentially eliminated Israel's motivation to make concessions in the West Bank, Gaza, or other areas.<ref>{{cite book|author=Kathleen Christison|title=Perceptions of Palestine: Their Influence on U.S. Middle East Policy|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Perceptions_of_Palestine&pg=PA|year=|publisher=University of California Press, 2000 |isbn=978-0-520-21718-8|quote=Because Egypt was the strongest Arab country and the only one able to pose a significant military threat to Israel, its removal as a factor in the Arab-Israeli conflict seriously reduced the military and diplomatic leverage of all the other Arab parties and removed virtually all incentive for Israel to make concessions in the West Bank and Gaza or on any other front.}}</ref>

===Madrid (1991–1993)===
{{main|Madrid Conference of 1991}}
Delegations from Israel, Syria, Lebanon, and Jordan accepted the invitation from US President [[George H. W. Bush]] and the Soviet Union president [[Mikhail Gorbachev]] to attend the [[Madrid Conference of 1991]],<ref>[http://www.mideastweb.org/madridconference.htm ''The Madrid Peace Conference''] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180330003449/http://www.mideastweb.org/madridconference.htm |date=30 March 2018 }}. MidEastWeb, 30 October 1991</ref> after the [[Gulf War|First Gulf War]].<ref>Eran, Oded. "Arab-Israel Peacemaking". ''The Continuum Political Encyclopedia of the Middle East''. Ed. [[Avraham Sela]]. New York: Continuum, 2002, p. 137.</ref>

===Oslo (1993–2001)===
{{main|Oslo Accords}}
[[File:Bill Clinton, Yitzhak Rabin, Yasser Arafat at the White House 1993-09-13.jpg|right|thumb|300px|[[Yitzhak Rabin]], [[Bill Clinton]], and [[Yasser Arafat]] at the Oslo Accords signing ceremony on 13 September 1993]]
While the slow moving Madrid talks were taking place, a series of secret meetings between Israeli and Palestinian negotiators were taking place in [[Oslo]], [[Norway]], which resulted in the [[1993 Oslo Peace Accords between Palestinians and Israel]], a plan discussing the necessary elements and conditions for a future [[Palestinian state]] "on the basis of [[United Nations Security Council Resolution 242|Security Council Resolutions 242]] and [[United Nations Security Council Resolution 338|338]]".<ref>Eran, Oded. "Arab-Israel Peacemaking". ''The Continuum Political Encyclopedia of the Middle East''. Ed. [[Avraham Sela]]. New York: Continuum, 2002, p. 138.</ref> The agreement, officially titled the [[Declaration of Principles on Interim Self-Government Arrangements]] (DOP), was signed on the [[White House]] lawn on 13 September 1993.  The stipulations of the Oslo agreements were criticized{{whom|date=August 2025}} as diverging from prevailing interpretations of how the conflict should be resolved; critics{{who|date=August 2025}} argued that the agreements failed to guarantee Palestinian self-determination or statehood and departed from one interpretation of UN Resolution 242, which holds that land cannot be acquired by war.<ref name="pop christison">{{cite book |first=Kathleen |last=Christison |title=Perceptions of Palestine |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=H6UwDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA|year=2000 |publisher=[[University of California Press]] |isbn=978-0-520-21718-8 |pages=290}}</ref> Political analyst Noam Chomsky argued that the Oslo agreements allowed Israel "to do virtually what it likes".<ref name="ft Chomsky">{{cite book |first=Noam |last=Chomsky |author-link=Noam Chomsky |title=Fateful Triangle |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=aHphMCIkhK0C&pg=PA |year=1999 |publisher=[[Pluto Press]] |isbn=978-0-7453-1530-0 |pages=Chapter 10}}</ref> Other observers, however, viewed the accords as a breakthrough that created a framework for mutual recognition and negotiations.<ref>[https://www.google.com/books/edition/The_Discourse_of_Palestinian_Israeli_Rel/Xq6MAgAAQBAJ?hl=en&gbpv=1&dq=oslo+israeli-palestinian+peace+process+breakthrough&pg=PA17&printsec=frontcover "The Discourse of Palestinian-Israeli Relations"]. ''Google Books''.  2010.  22 August 2025.</ref><ref>Waxman, Dov.  [https://www.google.com/books/edition/The_Israeli_Palestinian_Conflict/wTCPDwAAQBAJ?hl=en&gbpv=1&dq=oslo+israeli-palestinian+peace+process+breakthrough&pg=PA152&printsec=frontcover "The Israeli-Palestinian Conflict"]. ''Google Books''.  2019.  22 August 2025.</ref>

Various "transfers of power and responsibilities" in the Gaza Strip and West Bank from Israel to the Palestinians took place in the mid-1990s.<ref>''Facts About Israel''. Jerusalem: Israel Ministry of Foreign Affairs, 2010. p. 53.</ref> Israeli foreign minister Shlomo Ben-Ami described the Oslo Accords as legitimizing "the transformation of the West Bank into what has been called a 'cartographic cheeseboard'". Indeed, Oslo legitimized the fragmentation of Palestinian population centers by Jewish-only settlements and bypass roads, Israeli checkpoints, and military installations.<ref name="sowwop">{{cite book |first=Shlomo |last=Ben-Ami |title=Scars of War, Wounds of Peace |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=x72ZEAAAQBAJ&pg=PA |year=2007 |publisher=[[Oxford University Press]] |isbn=978-0-19-532542-3 |pages=241}}</ref> Core to the Oslo Accords was the creation of the Palestinian Authority and the security cooperation it would enter into with the Israeli military authorities.  Ben-Ami, who participated in the Camp David 2000 talks, described this process: "One of the meanings of Oslo was that the PLO was eventually Israel's collaborator in the task of stifling the Intifada and cutting short what was clearly an authentically democratic struggle for Palestinian independence."<ref name="sowwop"/>

After the assassination of [[Yitzhak Rabin]] in 1995, the peace process eventually ground to a halt. The settlements' population almost doubled in the West Bank. Later [[suicide bombing]] attacks from Palestinian militant groups and the subsequent retaliatory actions from the [[Israeli military]] made conditions for peace negotiations untenable.

===1996–1999 agreements===
Newly elected Prime Minister [[Benjamin Netanyahu]] declared a new policy following the many suicide attacks by [[Hamas]] and [[Palestinian Islamic Jihad]] since 1993, including a [[Jerusalem bus 18 massacres#Wave of attacks|wave of suicide attacks]] before the [[1996 Israeli general election|Israeli elections of May 1996]]. Netanyahu declared a [[tit-for-tat]] policy which he termed "reciprocity", whereby Israel would not engage in the peace process if Arafat continued with what Netanyahu defined as the [[Revolving door policy (alleged Palestinian Authority policy)|Palestinian revolving door policy]], i.e., incitement and direct or indirect support of terrorism. The [[Hebron Agreement|Hebron]] and [[Wye Agreement]]s were signed during this period, after Israel considered that its conditions were partially met.

The Protocol Concerning the Redeployment in Hebron, also known as the Hebron Protocol or [[Hebron Agreement]], began on 7 January and was concluded between Israel and the [[PLO]] from 15 to 17 January 1997. The agreement dealt with the redeployment of Israeli military forces in Hebron in accordance with the Oslo Accords, security issues, and other concerns.

The [[Wye River Memorandum]] was a political agreement negotiated to implement the Oslo Accords, completed on 23 October 1998. It was signed by Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu and PLO Chairman Yasser Arafat. It was negotiated at Wye River, Maryland (at the Wye River Conference Center) and signed at the White House with President [[Bill Clinton]] as the official witness. On 17 November 1998, Israel's 120-member parliament, the [[Knesset]], approved the Memorandum by voting 75–19. The agreement dealt with further redeployments in the West Bank, security issues, and other concerns. Major international human rights organizations criticized the memorandum for its "encouragement" of human rights abuses.<ref>Human Rights Watch, An Analysis of the Wye River Memorandum</ref><ref>Amnesty International, The United States, Israel and the Palestinian Authority: Human Rights Neglected in the Theory and Practice by All Involved in "Peacemaking"</ref>

===Camp David 2000 Summit, Clinton's "Parameters", and the Taba talks===
{{main|2000 Camp David Summit}}
In 2000, US President Bill Clinton convened a peace summit between Palestinian President Yasser Arafat and Israeli Prime Minister [[Ehud Barak]]. In May of that year, according to [[Nathan Thrall]], Israel had offered Palestinians 66% of the West Bank, with 17% annexed to Israel, and a further 17% not annexed but under Israeli control, and no compensating swap of Israeli territory.<ref name="Thrall" /> The Israeli prime minister offered the Palestinian leader between 91%<ref group="note">The 91% land offer was based on the Israeli definition of the West Bank, but this differs by approximately 5 percentage points from the Palestinian definition. Palestinians use a total area of 5,854 square kilometers. Israel, however, omits the area known as No Man's Land (50 km<sup>2</sup> near Latrun), post-1967 East Jerusalem (71 km<sup>2</sup>), and the territorial waters of the Dead Sea (195 km<sup>2</sup>), which reduces the total to 5,538 km<sup>2</sup>. Thus, an Israeli offer of 91% (of 5,538 km<sup>2</sup>) of the West Bank translates into only 86% from the Palestinian perspective. <br /> Jeremy Pressman, ''International Security'', vol 28, no. 2, Fall 2003, [http://belfercenter.ksg.harvard.edu/files/pressman.pdf ''"Visions in Collision: What Happened at Camp David and Taba?"''] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304082619/http://belfercenter.ksg.harvard.edu/files/pressman.pdf|date=4 March 2016}}. On [http://belfercenter.ksg.harvard.edu/publication/322/visions_in_collision.html] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110722061359/http://belfercenter.ksg.harvard.edu/publication/322/visions_in_collision.html|date=22 July 2011}}. See pp. 16–17</ref> and 95%<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2000/12/27/opinion/mr-clinton-s-mideast-peace-plan.html "Mr. Clinton's Mideast Peace Plan"]. {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191211010903/https://www.nytimes.com/2000/12/27/opinion/mr-clinton-s-mideast-peace-plan.html |date=11 December 2019 }} ''The New York Times''.  27 December 2000.  10 December 2019.</ref><ref>[https://www.adl.org/resources/glossary-terms/camp-david-summit-2000 "Camp David Summit 2000"]. {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191211010830/https://www.adl.org/resources/glossary-terms/camp-david-summit-2000 |date=11 December 2019 }} ''ADL''.  10 December 2019.</ref> (sources differ on the exact percentage) of the West Bank and the entire Gaza Strip if 69 Jewish settlements (which comprise 85% of the West Bank's Jewish settlers) were ceded to Israel. [[East Jerusalem]] would have fallen for the most part<ref>[https://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/middle_east/6666393.stm History of failed peace talks (BBC, 26 November 2007)] .</ref> under Israeli sovereignty, with the exception of most suburbs with heavy non-Jewish populations surrounded by areas annexed to Israel.<ref>[[Dore Gold|Gold, Dore]]. ''The Fight for Jerusalem: Radical Islam, the West, and the Future of the Holy City''. Washington, DC: Regnery Publishing, Inc., 2007. p. 1.</ref> The issue of the [[Palestinian right of return]] would be solved through significant monetary reparations.<ref>[[Michael B. Oren|Oren, Michael B.]] ''Power, Faith, and Fantasy: American in the Middle East, 1776 to the Present''. New York: W. W. Norton & Company, 2007. p. 579.</ref>

Arafat rejected this offer and did not propose a counteroffer.<ref name="Ross">[[Dennis Ross|Ross, Dennis]].  ''Doomed to Succeed: The U.S.-Israel Relationship From Truman to Obama''.  New York: Farrar, Starus and Giroux, 2015.  p. 293.</ref><ref>Ben-Meir, Alon. "The Palestinian Refugees: A Reassessment and a Solution". Palestine – Israel Journal of Politics, Economics, and Culture, vol. 15/16, no. 4, 2009, pp. 65-71. ProQuest.</ref><ref name="Hirsh">Hirsh, Michael.  [https://www.newsweek.com/clinton-arafat-its-all-your-fault-153779 "Clinton To Arafat: it's All Your ..."]. {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201211183211/https://www.newsweek.com/clinton-arafat-its-all-your-fault-153779 |date=11 December 2020 }} ''Newsweek''.  26 June 2001.  17 November 2020.</ref> No tenable solution was crafted which would satisfy both Israeli and Palestinian demands, even under intense U.S. pressure.<ref name="Ross" /> Clinton blamed Arafat for the failure of the Camp David Summit.<ref name="Ross" /><ref name="Hirsh" /> In the months following the summit, Clinton appointed former [[US Senator]] [[George J. Mitchell]] to lead a fact-finding committee that later published the [[Mitchell Report (Arab-Israeli conflict)|Mitchell Report]].

Proposed in the fall of 2000 following the collapse of the Camp David talks, [[The Clinton Parameters]] included a plan on which the Palestinian State was to include 94-96% of the West Bank. Around 80% of the [[Israeli settlement|settlers]] were to become under Israeli sovereignty. In exchange for that, Israel would concede some territory (so-called 'Territory Exchange' or 'Land Swap') within the [[Green Line (Israel)|Green Line]] (1967 borders). The swap would consist of 1–3% of Israeli territory, such that the final borders of the West Bank part of the Palestinian state would include 97% of the land of the original borders.<ref>[http://www.peacelobby.org/clinton_parameters.htm Clinton Parameters] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150117011736/http://www.peacelobby.org/clinton_parameters.htm |date=17 January 2015 }}, The Jewish Peace Lobby website, full text (English).</ref>

At the [[Taba summit]] (at [[Taba (Egypt)|Taba]]) in January 2001, talks continued based on the Clinton Parameters. The Israeli negotiation team presented a new map. The proposition removed the "temporarily Israeli-controlled" areas from the West Bank and offered a few thousand more refugees than they offered at Camp David to settle into Israel, and hoped that this would be considered "implementation" of [[United Nations General Assembly Resolution 194]].<ref>Beilin, Yossi.  [http://prrn.mcgill.ca/prrn/papers/beilin.html "What really happened at Taba"]. {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220313071415/http://prrn.mcgill.ca/prrn/papers/beilin.html |date=13 March 2022 }} ''Palestinian Refugee ResearchNet''.  16 July 2002.  10 December 2020.</ref><ref>Salem, Tanja.  [http://aei.pitt.edu/59088/1/1042.pdf "Palestinian Refugees"]. {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210624091452/https://aei.pitt.edu/59088/1/1042.pdf |date=24 June 2021 }} ''Centre for European Policy Studies''.  July 2003.</ref> The Palestinian side accepted this as a basis for further negotiation.  However, Barak did not conduct further negotiations at that time; the talks ended without an agreement, and the following month, the [[right-wing]] [[Likud]] party candidate [[Ariel Sharon]] was elected Israeli prime minister in February 2001.

===The Arab peace initiative and the Roadmap (2002-03)===
{{main||Arab Peace Initiative|Road map for peace|Beirut Summit}}
The Beirut summit of Arab government leaders took place in March 2002 under the aegis of the [[Arab League]]. The summit concluded by presenting a plan to end the Israeli-Palestinian conflict. [[Israeli Foreign Minister]] [[Shimon Peres]] welcomed it and said, "... the details of every peace plan must be discussed directly between Israel and the Palestinians, and to make this possible, the [[Palestinian Authority]] must put an end to terror, the horrifying expression of which we witnessed just last night in [[Netanya]]",<ref>{{cite web| url = http://www.mfa.gov.il/MFA/About+the+Ministry/MFA+Spokesman/2002/Response+of+FM+Peres+to+the+decisions+of+the+Arab.htm| url-status = dead| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20060110120946/http://www.mfa.gov.il/MFA/About+the+Ministry/MFA+Spokesman/2002/Response+of+FM+Peres+to+the+decisions+of+the+Arab.htm| archive-date = 2006-01-10| title = Response of FM Peres to the decisions of the Arab Summit in Beirut – 28-Mar-2002}}</ref> referring to the [[Netanya suicide attack]] perpetrated on the previous evening which the Beirut Summit failed to address. Israel was not prepared to enter negotiations as called for by the Arab League plan on the grounds that it did not wish for "full withdrawal to [[1967 borders]] and the [[right of return]] for the [[Palestinian refugees]]".<ref>Eran, Oded. "Arab-Israel Peacemaking". ''The Continuum Political Encyclopedia of the Middle East''. Ed. [[Avraham Sela]]. New York: Continuum, 2002, p. 147.</ref>

[[File:sharon bush abbas.jpg|thumb|right|250px|President [[George W. Bush]], center, discusses the peace process with Prime Minister [[Ariel Sharon]] of Israel, left, and Palestinian President [[Mahmoud Abbas]] in [[Aqaba]], Jordan, 4 June 2003.]]
=== Israeli–Palestinian talks in 2007 and 2008 ===
{{further|Annapolis Conference}}
[[File:Realignment_plan_map_original.png|thumb|Olmert plan, publicised by Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Olmert in February 2025]]
From December 2006 to mid-September 2008, Israeli Prime Minister [[Ehud Olmert]] and President Mahmoud Abbas of the Palestinian Authority met 36 times; there were also lower-level talks. In 2007, Olmert welcomed the [[Arab League]]'s re-endorsement of the [[Arab Peace Initiative]]. In his bid to negotiate a peace accord and establish a Palestinian state, Olmert proposed a plan to the Palestinians.<ref name="Plan for Peace">[https://www.nytimes.com/2011/02/13/magazine/13Israel-t.html A Plan for Peace That Still Could Be] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190817105305/https://www.nytimes.com/2011/02/13/magazine/13Israel-t.html |date=17 August 2019 }}, ''New York Times Magazine'', 13 February 2011.</ref> The centerpiece of Olmert's detailed proposal is the suggested permanent border, which would be based on an Israeli withdrawal from most of the West Bank. Olmert proposed annexing at least 6.3% of Palestinian territory, in exchange for 5.8% of Israeli land, with Palestinians receiving alternative land in the Negev, adjacent to the Gaza Strip, as well as a territorial link, under Israeli sovereignty, for free passage between Gaza and the West Bank. Israel insisted on retaining an armed presence in the future Palestinian state.<ref name="Thrall">[[Nathan Thrall]], [http://www.nybooks.com/articles/archives/2013/aug/15/what-future-israel/ 'What Future for Israel?,'] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151121042418/http://www.nybooks.com/articles/archives/2013/aug/15/what-future-israel/ |date=21 November 2015 }} ''[[New York Review of Books]]'' 15 August 2013 pp. 64–67.</ref><ref name="Olmerts offer">[https://www.haaretz.com/news/pa-rejects-olmert-s-offer-to-withdraw-from-93-of-west-bank-1.251578 PA rejects Olmert's offer to withdraw from 93% of West Bank (Haaretz, 12 August 2008)] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180102174003/https://www.haaretz.com/news/pa-rejects-olmert-s-offer-to-withdraw-from-93-of-west-bank-1.251578 |date=2 January 2018 }}.</ref> Under Abbas's offer, more than 60 percent of settlers would stay in place. For his part, Olmert presented a plan in which the most sparsely populated settlements would be evacuated. Olmert and Abbas both acknowledged that reciprocal relations would be necessary, not hermetic separation. They also acknowledged the need to share a single business ecosystem, while cooperating intensively on water, security, bandwidth, banking, tourism, and much more. Regarding Jerusalem the leaders agreed that Jewish neighborhoods should remain under Israeli sovereignty and Arab neighborhoods would revert to Palestinian sovereignty.<ref name="Plan for Peace" /> The Palestinians asked for clarifications of the territorial land swap since they were unable to ascertain what land his percentages affected, since Israeli and Palestinian calculations of the West Bank differ by several hundred square kilometres. For them, in lieu of such clarifications, Olmert's 6.3–6.8% annexation might work out closer to 8.5%, 4 times the 1.9% limit the Palestinians argued a swap should not exceed.<ref name="Thrall" /> The talks ended with both sides claiming the other side dropped follow-up contacts.<ref name="Thrall" /><ref name="Olmerts offer" />

[[Government of Egypt|Egypt]] brokered the [[2008 Israel–Hamas ceasefire]], which lasted half a year beginning on 19 June 2008 and lasted until 19 December 2008.<ref name=NYTimes-truce>[https://www.nytimes.com/2008/06/18/world/middleeast/18mideast.html?_r=2&fta=y Israel Agrees to Truce with Hamas on Gaza] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190228094231/https://www.nytimes.com/2008/06/18/world/middleeast/18mideast.html?_r=2&fta=y |date=28 February 2019 }}, ''[[The New York Times]]'', 18 June 2008.</ref> The collapse of the ceasefire led to the [[Gaza War (2008–09)|Gaza War]] on 27 December 2008.

===2010 direct talks===
{{Main|2010–2011 Israeli–Palestinian peace talks}}
{{See also|2010 Palestinian militancy campaign}}

In June 2009, reacting to US President Barack Obama's [[A New Beginning (speech)|Cairo Address]],<ref name="Thrall" /> Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu declared for the first time<ref>Mark Tessler, "The Israeli–Palestinian Conflict", in Ellen Lust (ed.),[https://books.google.com/books?id=9loXBAAAQBAJ&pg=PA364 ''The Middle East''], [[SAGE Publications]], 2013 pp. 287–366, p. 364.</ref> conditional support for a future Palestinian state<ref>[https://www.haaretz.com/print-edition/opinion/netanyahu-s-revolution-1.278309 Netanyahu's revolution] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924232245/http://www.haaretz.com/print-edition/opinion/netanyahu-s-revolution-1.278309 |date=24 September 2015 }}, ''Haaretz'', 18 June 2009</ref> but insisted that the Palestinians would need to make reciprocal gestures and accept several principles: recognition of Israel as the nation-state of the Jewish people; demilitarization of a future Palestinian state, along with additional security guarantees, including defensible borders for Israel;<ref>[https://www.haaretz.com/news/full-text-of-netanyahu-s-foreign-policy-speech-at-bar-ilan-1.277922 Full text of Netanyahu's foreign policy speech at Bar Ilan] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180101042731/https://www.haaretz.com/news/full-text-of-netanyahu-s-foreign-policy-speech-at-bar-ilan-1.277922 |date=1 January 2018 }}, ''[[Haaretz]]'', 14 June 2009.</ref> acceptance that Jerusalem would remain the united capital of Israel; and renunciation of their claim to a [[right of return]]. He also claimed that Israeli settlements retain the right to growth and expansion in the West Bank. Palestinians rejected the proposals immediately.<ref>Dan Cohn-Sherbok, Dawoud El-Alami, [https://books.google.com/books?id=fVgQBwAAQBAJ&pg=PT87 ''The Palestine–Israeli Conflict: A Beginner's Guide''], [[Oneworld Publications]] 2015 p. 87.</ref> In September 2010, the [[Obama administration]] pushed to revive the stalled peace process by getting the parties involved to agree to direct talks for the first time in about two years.<ref name="ap090110">{{cite news |url=https://abcnews.go.com/Politics/wirestory?id=11523733&page=1 |title=Obama Opens Long-Shot Talks on Mideast Peace |author=Burns, Robert |agency=[[Associated Press]] |publisher=[[ABC News (United States)|ABC News]] |date=1 September 2010 |access-date=16 April 2020 |archive-date=10 November 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101110051524/http://abcnews.go.com/Politics/wirestory?id=11523733&page=1 |url-status=live }}</ref> While U.S. President [[Barack Obama]] was the orchestrator of the movement, U.S. Secretary of State [[Hillary Clinton]] went through months of cajoling just to get the parties to the table, and helped convince the reluctant Palestinians by getting support for direct talks from Egypt and Jordan.<ref name="ap090110"/><ref name="nyt-me-test">{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/09/05/world/middleeast/05clinton.html |title=In Middle East Peace Talks, Clinton Faces a Crucial Test |author=[[Mark Landler|Landler, Mark]] |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |date=5 September 2010 |page=A1 |access-date=22 February 2017 |archive-date=23 March 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190323062620/https://www.nytimes.com/2010/09/05/world/middleeast/05clinton.html |url-status=live }}</ref> The aim of the talks was to forge the framework of a final agreement within one year, although general expectations of a success were fairly low. The talks aimed to put the Israeli–Palestinian conflict to an official end by forming a two-state solution for the Jewish and Palestinian peoples, promoting the idea of everlasting peace, and putting an official halt to any further land claims, as well as accepting the rejection of any forceful retribution if violence should recur. [[Hamas]] and [[Hezbollah]], however, threatened violence, especially if either side seemed likely to compromise in order to reach an agreement. As a result, the Israeli government publicly stated that peace couldn't exist even if both sides signed the agreement, due to the stance taken by [[Hamas]] and [[Hezbollah]]. The US was therefore compelled to re-focus on eliminating the threat posed by the stance of Hamas and Hezbollah as part of the direct talks process. Israel, for its part, was skeptical that a final agreement would change the situation, as Hamas and Hezbollah would still get support to fuel new violence. In addition, the Israeli government rejected any possible agreement with Palestine as long as it refuses to recognize Israel as a Jewish state.

Since 1982, the mainstream within the PLO had shown interest in mutual recognition and a Palestinian state.<ref>Tessler, Mark A. [https://books.google.com/books?id=3kbU4BIAcrQC ''A History of the Israeli–Palestinian Conflict''] Google Books. Originally published in 1994. p. 718. "Inhabitants of the occupied territories and other Palestinians had shown serious interest in a two-state solution since the mid-1970s, and the mainstream of the PLO had, since the 1982 Arab summit in Fez, been officially committed to mutual recognition between Israel and a Palestinian state located in the West Bank and Gaza, with East Jerusalem as its capital."</ref> During the 2010 talks, Palestinian Authority President [[Mahmoud Abbas]] said that the Palestinians and Israel had agreed on the principle of a land swap, but Israel had yet to confirm. The issue of the ratio of land Israel would give to the Palestinians in exchange for keeping settlement blocs was an issue of dispute, with the Palestinians demanding that the ratio be 1:1, and Israel offering less.<ref>{{cite news|last=Abu Toameh|first=Khaled|title=Abbas: Land swap principle reached|url=https://www.jpost.com/MiddleEast/Article.aspx?id=176148|newspaper=[[The Jerusalem Post]]|access-date=23 June 2010|archive-date=26 November 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121126061000/http://www.jpost.com/MiddleEast/Article.aspx?id=176148|url-status=live}}</ref> In April 2012, [[Mahmoud Abbas]] sent a letter to [[Benjamin Netanyahu]] reiterating that for peace talks to resume, Israel must stop settlement building in the West Bank, including East Jerusalem, and accept the 1967 borders as a basis for a two-state solution.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/04/18/world/middleeast/palestinians-deliver-letter-on-peace-talks-to-netanyahu.html |title=Palestinians Restate Demands to Netanyahu |last=Bronner |first=Ethan |date=17 April 2012 |work=The New York Times |access-date=18 April 2012 |archive-date=28 February 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190228094829/https://www.nytimes.com/2012/04/18/world/middleeast/palestinians-deliver-letter-on-peace-talks-to-netanyahu.html |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.timesofisrael.com/text-of-abbass-letter-to-netanyahu/ |title=Text of Abbas's letter to Netanyahu |author=Mahmoud Abbas |date=15 April 2012 |newspaper=The Times of Israel |access-date=18 April 2012 |archive-date=18 April 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120418002240/http://www.timesofisrael.com/text-of-abbass-letter-to-netanyahu/ |url-status=live }}</ref> In May 2012, Abbas reiterated his readiness to engage with the Israelis if they propose "anything promising or positive".<ref>{{cite news |url=http://english.alarabiya.net/articles/2012/05/09/212947.html |title=Abbas ready to engage with Israel but says settlement building 'destroying hope' |last1=Stott |first1=Michael |last2=Nakhoul |first2=Samia |date=9 May 2012 |agency=Reuters |publisher=Al Arabiya News |access-date=9 May 2012 |archive-date=9 May 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120509035627/http://english.alarabiya.net/articles/2012/05/09/212947.html |url-status=live }}</ref> Netanyahu replied to Abbas' April letter less than a week later and, for the first time, officially recognised the right for Palestinians to have their own state, though as before<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.haaretz.com/news/netanyahu-backs-demilitarized-palestinian-state-1.277915 |title=Netanyahu backs demilitarized Palestinian state |date=14 June 2009 |newspaper=Haaretz |access-date=14 May 2012 |archive-date=31 May 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110531053243/http://www.haaretz.com/news/netanyahu-backs-demilitarized-palestinian-state-1.277915 |url-status=live }}</ref> he declared it would have to be demilitarised,<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.timesofisrael.com/netanyahu-pledges-to-establish-demilitarized-palestinian-state/ |title=PM promises Abbas a demilitarized Palestinian state |last1=Winer |first1=Stuart |last2=Ahren |first2=Raphael |date=14 May 2012 |newspaper=The Times of Israel |access-date=14 May 2012 |archive-date=17 May 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120517003049/http://www.timesofisrael.com/netanyahu-pledges-to-establish-demilitarized-palestinian-state/ |url-status=live }}</ref> and said his new national unity government furnished a new opportunity to renew negotiations and move forward.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.haaretz.com/news/diplomacy-defense/netanyahu-to-abbas-israeli-unity-cabinet-is-a-new-opportunity-for-mideast-peace-1.430224 |title=Netanyahu to Abbas: Israeli unity cabinet is a new opportunity for Mideast peace |last=Ravid |first=Barak |date=14 May 2012 |newspaper=Haaretz |access-date=14 May 2012 |archive-date=14 May 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120514173048/http://www.haaretz.com/news/diplomacy-defense/netanyahu-to-abbas-israeli-unity-cabinet-is-a-new-opportunity-for-mideast-peace-1.430224 |url-status=live }}</ref>

===2013–14 talks===
{{main|2013–2014 Israeli–Palestinian peace talks}}
Direct negotiations between Israel and the Palestinians began on 29 July 2013 following an attempt by United States Secretary of State [[John Kerry]] to restart the peace process.

[[Martin Indyk]] of the Brookings Institution in Washington, D.C., was appointed by the US to oversee the negotiations. Indyk served as U.S. ambassador to Israel and assistant secretary of state for Near East affairs during the Clinton administration.<ref>{{cite news|last=Ravid|first=Barak|title=Obama welcomes renewal of Israeli-Palestinian talks, but says 'hard choices' lie ahead|url=https://www.haaretz.com/news/diplomacy-defense/1.538586|access-date=7 February 2014|newspaper=Haaretz|date=29 July 2013|archive-date=12 May 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150512205014/http://www.haaretz.com/news/diplomacy-defense/1.538586|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Hamas]], the Palestinian [[Governance of the Gaza Strip|government in Gaza]], rejected Kerry's announcement, stating that Palestinian president [[Mahmoud Abbas]] has no legitimacy to negotiate in the name of the Palestinian people.<ref>{{cite news|title=Hamas rejects Kerry's announcement: Abbas has no authority to negotiate|newspaper=Ynetnews|url=http://www.ynetnews.com/articles/0,7340,L-4407236,00.html|publisher=Ynet|access-date=23 July 2013|date=20 July 2013|archive-date=19 August 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190819102446/https://www.ynetnews.com/articles/0,7340,L-4407236,00.html|url-status=live}}</ref>

The negotiations were scheduled to last up to nine months to reach a final status to the Palestinian-Israeli conflict by mid-2014. The Israeli negotiating team was led by veteran negotiator Justice Minister [[Tzipi Livni]], while the Palestinian delegation was led by [[Saeb Erekat]], also a former negotiator. Negotiations started in Washington, DC<ref name="wapo">{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/middle_east/israel-to-free-104-palestinian-prisoners/2013/07/28/390ad8d2-f7a3-11e2-a954-358d90d5d72d_story.html|title=Peace talks set to begin after Israel agrees to free 104 Palestinian prisoners|newspaper=The Washington Post|first=William|last=Booth|date=29 July 2013|access-date=6 October 2019|archive-date=7 July 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190707212919/https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/middle_east/israel-to-free-104-palestinian-prisoners/2013/07/28/390ad8d2-f7a3-11e2-a954-358d90d5d72d_story.html|url-status=live}}</ref> and were slated to move to the [[King David Hotel]] in Jerusalem and finally to Hebron.<ref>Berman, Lazar. (7 August 2013) [http://www.timesofisrael.com/us-peace-envoy-to-come-to-israel-next-week/ US peace envoy to come to Israel next week] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171102222454/https://www.timesofisrael.com/us-peace-envoy-to-come-to-israel-next-week/ |date=2 November 2017 }}. [[The Times of Israel]]. Retrieved 14 August 2013.</ref> A deadline was set for establishing a broad outline for an agreement by 29 April 2014. On the expiry of the deadline, negotiations collapsed, with the US Special Envoy Indyk reportedly assigning blame mainly to Israel. The [[United States Department of State|US State Department]] insisted no one side was to blame but that "both sides did things that were incredibly unhelpful".<ref>AFP, [http://www.ynetnews.com/articles/0,7340,L-4516768,00.html 'US denies dismantling peace negotiators team,'] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171102221712/https://www.ynetnews.com/articles/0,7340,L-4516768,00.html |date=2 November 2017 }} [[Ynet]], 6 May 2014.</ref>

Israel reacted angrily to the [[2014 Fatah–Hamas Agreements|Fatah–Hamas Gaza Agreement of 23 April 2014]], whose main purpose was reconciliation between Fatah and Hamas, the formation of a Palestinian unity government, and the holding of new elections.<ref name=bbc20140423>{{cite news|title=Hamas and Fatah unveil Palestinian reconciliation deal|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-middle-east-27128902|publisher=BBC|date=23 April 2014|access-date=6 October 2019|archive-date=18 July 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150718125328/http://www.bbc.com/news/world-middle-east-27128902|url-status=live}}</ref> Israel halted peace talks with the Palestinians, saying it "will not negotiate with a Palestinian government backed by Hamas, a terrorist organization that calls for Israel's destruction", and threatened sanctions against the Palestinian Authority,<ref name="ynetnews20140424">[http://www.ynetnews.com/articles/0,7340,L-4513046,00.html Sanctions and suspended talks – Israel responds to Palestinian reconciliation] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171103195342/https://www.ynetnews.com/articles/0,7340,L-4513046,00.html |date=3 November 2017 }} [[Ynet News]] 24 April 2014</ref><ref name=guardian_halts_peace>[https://www.theguardian.com/world/2014/apr/24/middle-east-israel-halts-peace-talks-palestinians ''Israel suspends peace talks with Palestinians after Fatah-Hamas deal''] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191006044526/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2014/apr/24/middle-east-israel-halts-peace-talks-palestinians |date=6 October 2019 }}. ''The Guardian'', 24 April 2014</ref> including a previously announced Israeli plan to unilaterally deduct Palestinian debts to Israeli companies from the tax revenue Israel collects for the PA.<ref>[https://www.latimes.com/world/middleeast/la-fg-israel-talks-20140425-story.html ''Israel suspends peace talks with Palestinians''] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191006044537/https://www.latimes.com/world/middleeast/la-fg-israel-talks-20140425-story.html |date=6 October 2019 }}. Batsheva Sobelman, ''Los Angeles Times'', 24 April 2014</ref> Israeli Prime Minister [[Benjamin Netanyahu]] accused Abbas of sabotaging peace efforts. He said that Abbas cannot have peace with both Hamas and Israel and has to choose.<ref name=guardian_landmark_pact>[https://web.archive.org/web/20140424031035/http://www.theguardian.com/world/2014/apr/23/plo-hamas-agree-unity-pact-form-government ''Fatah and Hamas agree landmark pact after seven-year rift'']. Peter Beaumont and Paul Lewis, ''The Guardian'', 24 April 2014</ref><ref name=france24_rival_leaderships>[http://www.france24.com/en/20140423-fatah-hamas-agree-palestinian-unity-government/ ''The rival Palestinian leaderships of Fatah and Hamas made a fresh attempt ...''] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140424015211/http://www.france24.com/en/20140423-fatah-hamas-agree-palestinian-unity-government/ |date=24 April 2014 }}. France 24/AP, 23 April 2014</ref> Abbas said the deal did not contradict their commitment to peace with Israel on the basis of a two-state solution<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-middle-east-27128902|title=Hamas and Fatah unveil Palestinian reconciliation deal|date=23 April 2014|access-date=6 October 2019|archive-date=6 October 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191006044525/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-middle-east-27128902|url-status=live}}</ref> and assured reporters that any unity government would recognize Israel, be non-violent, and bound to previous PLO agreements.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.sabc.co.za/news/a/350bab0043d15ec68f158ff0c0fe2c4c/PLO,-Hamas-unity-constitute-reuniting-West-Bank-and-Gaza:-Ban-Ki-moon|title=PLO, Hamas unity constitute reuniting West Bank and Gaza: Ban Ki-moon|date=29 April 2014|access-date=1 May 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924093607/http://www.sabc.co.za/news/a/350bab0043d15ec68f158ff0c0fe2c4c/PLO,-Hamas-unity-constitute-reuniting-West-Bank-and-Gaza:-Ban-Ki-moon|archive-date=24 September 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref> Shortly after, Israel began implementing economic sanctions against Palestinians and canceled plans to build housing for Palestinians in Area C of the West Bank.<ref>[http://www.ynetnews.com/articles/0,7340,L-4514309,00.html Israel begins implementing economic sanctions against Palestinians] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171103192334/https://www.ynetnews.com/articles/0,7340,L-4514309,00.html |date=3 November 2017 }} [[Ynet News]] 29 April 2014</ref> Abbas also threatened to dissolve the PA, leaving Israel fully responsible for both the West Bank and Gaza,<ref>New York Times, 22 April 2014,[https://www.nytimes.com/2014/04/23/world/middleeast/abbas-palestinian-authority.html Abbas Renews Threat to Dissolve Palestinian Authority if Peace Talks Fail] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191006041945/https://www.nytimes.com/2014/04/23/world/middleeast/abbas-palestinian-authority.html |date=6 October 2019 }}</ref> a threat that the PA has not put into effect.<ref>Rasgon, Adam.  [https://www.jpost.com/Arab-Israeli-Conflict/Palestinian-leadership-considers-dissolving-PA-says-Abbas-insider-503268 "Palestinian Leadership Considers ..."]. {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191104190725/https://www.jpost.com/Arab-Israeli-Conflict/Palestinian-leadership-considers-dissolving-PA-says-Abbas-insider-503268 |date=4 November 2019 }} ''The Jerusalem Post''.  23 August 2017.  4 November 2019.</ref>

Notwithstanding Israeli objections and actions, the new [[Palestinian unity government of 2014|Palestinian Unity Government]] was formed on 2 June 2014.<ref name="ynetnews20140424"/>

===Abbas' 2014 peace plan===
On 3 September 2014, Abbas presented a new proposal for the peace process to John Kerry.<ref>[http://www.israelnationalnews.com/News/News.aspx/184363 Abbas to Submit 'Surprising' Proposal to Kerry] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190108233951/http://www.israelnationalnews.com/News/News.aspx/184363 |date=8 January 2019 }} – Retrieved 4 September 2014</ref><ref name=reject>[https://www.jpost.com/Arab-Israeli-Conflict/PA-says-US-rejected-Abbass-peace-plan-374491 US rejected Abbas's peace plan, PA says] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190701122748/https://www.jpost.com/Arab-Israeli-Conflict/PA-says-US-rejected-Abbass-peace-plan-374491 |date=1 July 2019 }} – Retrieved 4 September 2014</ref> The plan called for nine months of direct talks followed by a three-year plan for Israel to withdraw to the 1967 lines, leaving East Jerusalem as Palestine's capital.<ref>[https://www.bloomberg.com/news/2014-09-03/abbas-peace-plan-calls-for-israeli-withdrawal-within-3-years.html Abbas Peace Plan Calls for Israeli Withdrawal Within 3 Years] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150110032344/http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2014-09-03/abbas-peace-plan-calls-for-israeli-withdrawal-within-3-years.html |date=10 January 2015 }} – Retrieved 4 September 2014</ref> The resumption of talks was contingent on an Israeli freeze on construction in the West Bank and east Jerusalem,<ref name=Abbasplan>[http://www.philly.com/philly/news/nation_world/20140904_Report__Abbas_peace_plan_calls_for_Israeli_withdrawal_from_West_Bank.html Report: Abbas peace plan calls for Israeli withdrawal from West Bank] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190531145119/https://www.philly.com/philly/news/nation_world/20140904_Report__Abbas_peace_plan_calls_for_Israeli_withdrawal_from_West_Bank.html |date=31 May 2019 }} – Retrieved 4 September 2014</ref> as well as the release of the final batch of prisoners from the previous talks.<ref>[https://www.haaretz.com/news/diplomacy-defense/1.613677 Abbas' peace plan: Israeli withdrawal from West Bank within three years] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150512203505/http://www.haaretz.com/news/diplomacy-defense/1.613677 |date=12 May 2015 }} – Retrieved 4 September 2014</ref> The first three months of the plan would revolve around the borders and potential land swaps for the 1967 lines. The following six months would focus on issues including refugees, Jerusalem, settlements, security and water.<ref>[http://www.theyeshivaworld.com/news/headlines-breaking-stories/256890/abu-mazens-three-year-peace-plan-for-israel.html Abu Mazen's Three-Year Peace Plan for Israel] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190711200441/https://www.theyeshivaworld.com/news/headlines-breaking-stories/256890/abu-mazens-three-year-peace-plan-for-israel.html |date=11 July 2019 }} – Retrieved 4 September 2014</ref> The US administration rejected the initiative, saying it was opposed to any unilateral move that could negatively impact the Israeli–Palestinian peace process.<ref name=reject/>

Abbas stated that if Israel rejected the claim he would push for charges against Israel in the [[International Criminal Court]] over the [[2014 Israel–Gaza conflict]].<ref name=Abbasplan/> Additionally, if rejected, Abbas stated he would turn to the UN Security Council for a unilateral measure for a Palestinian State.<ref name=reject /> On 1 October 2014, Abbas stated he would be presenting his plan to the UNSC within two to three weeks, with an application to the ICC to follow if it failed to pass the UNSC.<ref>[https://www.jpost.com/Arab-Israeli-Conflict/Abbas-If-Security-Council-bid-fails-we-will-join-ICC-may-end-security-cooperation-with-Israel-376739 Abbas: If Security Council bid fails, we may end security cooperation with Israel] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190611005143/https://www.jpost.com/Arab-Israeli-Conflict/Abbas-If-Security-Council-bid-fails-we-will-join-ICC-may-end-security-cooperation-with-Israel-376739 |date=11 June 2019 }} – Retrieved 1 October 2014</ref> Later that month as previously threatened, Abbas signed the treaty to join the ICC.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-middle-east-30645462|title=Palestinians sign up to join ICC|publisher=BBC News|date=31 December 2014|access-date=19 March 2018|archive-date=28 November 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181128143303/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-middle-east-30645462|url-status=live}}</ref> Israel responded by freezing NIS 500 million (US$127 million) in Palestinian tax revenues,<ref>{{cite news|last1=Staff|title=Israel freezes Palestinian funds in response to ICC bid|url=http://www.timesofisrael.com/israel-freezes-palestinian-funds-after-icc-bid/|newspaper=The Times of Israel|access-date=7 February 2015|archive-date=28 January 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150128042527/http://www.timesofisrael.com/israel-freezes-palestinian-funds-after-icc-bid/|url-status=live}}</ref> in response to which, the PA banned the sale in the Palestinian territories of products of six major Israeli companies.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.jpost.com/Arab-Israeli-Conflict/Palestinians-to-ban-sale-of-products-from-6-major-Israeli-companies-390493|title=Palestinians to ban sale of products from 6 major Israeli companies|website=The Jerusalem Post|date=9 February 2015 |access-date=19 March 2018|archive-date=20 March 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180320050843/http://www.jpost.com/Arab-Israeli-Conflict/Palestinians-to-ban-sale-of-products-from-6-major-Israeli-companies-390493|url-status=live}}</ref>

===Trump plan===
{{further|2020 Trump Israel–Palestine plan}}
[[File:Trump Peace Plan Map.jpg|thumb|right|Trump plan map]]
Following the inauguration of US President [[Donald Trump]] in January 2017, a period of uncertainty regarding a new peace initiative began. In early 2018, some media sources reported that the new administration was preparing a new peace initiative for an Israeli-Palestinian deal.  The White House unveiled the economic part of the Trump initiative, titled ''Peace to Prosperity: The Economic Plan'', in June 2019,<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://trumpwhitehouse.archives.gov/wp-content/uploads/2019/06/MEP-narrative-document_FINAL.pdf |title=''Peace to Prosperity: The Economic Plan'' |access-date=28 February 2021 |archive-date=22 June 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210622201119/https://trumpwhitehouse.archives.gov/wp-content/uploads/2019/06/MEP-narrative-document_FINAL.pdf |url-status=live }}</ref> and the political portion of the plan in January 2020. Palestinian leaders boycotted and condemned the [[Bahrain]] conference in late June 2019 at which the economic plan was unveiled.

In December 2017, Palestinian president [[Mahmoud Abbas]] cut ties with the Trump administration after [[United States recognition of Jerusalem as capital of Israel]]. The Trump administration further raised Palestinians' ire when it moved the US embassy to Jerusalem in May 2018, and cut hundreds of millions of dollars in annual aid to the Palestinians, citing the PA's refusal to take part in the administration's peace initiative.<ref>Times of Israel, 26 September 2019, [https://www.timesofisrael.com/at-un-abbas-threatens-to-nix-agreements-with-israel-if-west-bank-land-annexed/ At UN, Abbas threatens to nix agreements with Israel if West Bank land annexed] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191002152917/https://www.timesofisrael.com/at-un-abbas-threatens-to-nix-agreements-with-israel-if-west-bank-land-annexed/ |date=2 October 2019 }}</ref>

===Munich group===
In February 2020, on the sidelines of the [[Munich Security Conference]], the foreign ministers of Egypt, France, Germany, and Jordan, the [[Munich Group]], together discussed peace efforts.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.diplomatie.gouv.fr/en/french-foreign-policy/security-disarmament-and-non-proliferation/news/2020/article/participation-of-jean-yves-le-drian-in-the-munich-security-conference|title=Participation of Jean-Yves Le Drian in the Munich Security Conference – Declaration by the Spokesperson of the Ministry for Europe and Foreign Affairs (15-16 Feb.20)|website=France Diplomacy – Ministry for Europe and Foreign Affairs|access-date=11 January 2021|archive-date=13 January 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210113124405/https://www.diplomatie.gouv.fr/en/french-foreign-policy/security-disarmament-and-non-proliferation/news/2020/article/participation-of-jean-yves-le-drian-in-the-munich-security-conference|url-status=live}}</ref> In July, the same quartet issued a statement declaring that "any annexation of Palestinian territories occupied in 1967 would be a violation of international law" and "would have serious consequences for the security and stability of the region and would constitute a major obstacle to efforts aimed at achieving a comprehensive and just peace". The foreign ministers said they "discussed how to restart a fruitful engagement between the Israeli and the Palestinian side, and offer our support in facilitating a path to negotiations".<ref name = "newQ" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.diplomatie.gouv.fr/en/country-files/israel-palestinian-territories/news/2020/article/joint-statement-of-the-foreign-ministers-of-france-germany-egypt-and-jordan-07|title=Joint Statement of the Foreign Ministers of France, Germany, Egypt and Jordan (7 Jul. 20)|website=France Diplomatie – Ministère de l'Europe et des Affaires étrangères|access-date=20 February 2022|archive-date=20 February 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220220112403/https://www.diplomatie.gouv.fr/en/country-files/israel-palestinian-territories/news/2020/article/joint-statement-of-the-foreign-ministers-of-france-germany-egypt-and-jordan-07|url-status=live}}</ref>

Meeting in Jordan on 24 September, the four again called for a resumption of negotiations between the two sides. There will be "no comprehensive and lasting peace without solving the conflict on the basis of the two-state solution", Jordanian Foreign Minister Ayman al-Safadi told reporters following the meeting. The four also praised recent deals establishing ties between [[Israel–United Arab Emirates normalization agreement|Israel and the United Arab Emirates]] and [[Bahrain–Israel normalization agreement|Bahrain]]. Egypt's [[Sameh Shoukry]] said the deals are an "important development that would lead to more support and interaction in order to reach a comprehensive peace". However, Palestinians see the two accords as a betrayal.<ref>{{cite news|title=Arab, European states call Israel and Palestine to restart talks|url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2020/9/24/four-arab-and-european-fms|publisher=Al Jazeera|date=24 September 2020|access-date=24 September 2020|archive-date=24 September 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200924144116/https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2020/9/24/four-arab-and-european-fms|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Amman's closing statement on the Middle East Peace Process|url=https://en.royanews.tv/news/22514/Amman%27s%20closing%20statement%20on%20the%20Middle%20East%20Peace%20Process|publisher=Roya news|date=24 September 2020|access-date=24 September 2020|archive-date=16 January 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210116075524/https://en.royanews.tv/news/22514/Amman%27s%20closing%20statement%20on%20the%20Middle%20East%20Peace%20Process|url-status=live}}</ref>

On 11 January 2021, the group met in Cairo to discuss "possible steps to advance the peace process in the Middle East and create an environment conducive to the resumption of dialogue between the Palestinians and the Israelis". A joint statement of the quartet confirmed its intention to work with the incoming administration of President-elect Joe Biden. A further meeting is set to be held in Paris.<ref>{{cite news|title=Egypt, Germany, France, Jordan meet to revive Mideast talks|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/the_americas/egypt-germany-france-jordan-meet-to-revive-mideast-talks/2021/01/11/77e2ab76-53fc-11eb-acc5-92d2819a1ccb_story.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210111201013/https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/the_americas/egypt-germany-france-jordan-meet-to-revive-mideast-talks/2021/01/11/77e2ab76-53fc-11eb-acc5-92d2819a1ccb_story.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=11 January 2021|publisher = WAPO|date= 11 January 2021|access-date=11 January 2021}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Arab, European foreign ministers discuss Palestinian, Israeli Occupation peace process in Cairo|url=https://en.royanews.tv/news/24752/Arab,%20European%20foreign%20ministers%20discuss%20Palestinian,%20Israeli%20Occupation%20peace%20process%20in%20Cairo|publisher=RoyaNews|date=11 January 2021|access-date=11 January 2021|archive-date=15 January 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210115040117/https://en.royanews.tv/news/24752/Arab,%20European%20foreign%20ministers%20discuss%20Palestinian,%20Israeli%20Occupation%20peace%20process%20in%20Cairo|url-status=live}}</ref>

The four met in Paris on 11 March 2021, with [[United Nations Special Coordinator for the Middle East Peace Process]] [[Tor Wennesland]] and the [[European Union Special Representative]] for the Middle East Peace Process, Susanna Terstal. Their statement emphasized the importance of confidence-building measures to promote dialogue and support the two-state solution, and stated that settlement activities violate international law.<ref>{{cite news|title=The Middle East, including the Palestinian Question: Briefing and Consultations|url=https://www.securitycouncilreport.org/whatsinblue/2021/03/the-middle-east-including-the-palestinian-question-briefing-and-consultations-2.php|publisher=SecurityCouncilReport|date=24 March 2021|access-date=24 March 2021|archive-date=25 March 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210325012532/https://www.securitycouncilreport.org/whatsinblue/2021/03/the-middle-east-including-the-palestinian-question-briefing-and-consultations-2.php|url-status=live}}</ref>

On 19 February 2021, at the [[Munich Security Conference]], as well as reaffirming support for a two state solution, the group condemned the expansion of Israeli settlements and the ongoing [[Palestinian displacement in East Jerusalem]], in particular in [[Sheikh Jarrah controversy|Sheikh Jarrah]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://english.alaraby.co.uk/news/fm-quartet-slams-israel-settlement-expansion-evictions|title=Egypt, France, Germany, Jordan FMs condemn Israel settlement expansion, evictions|date=20 February 2022|website=english.alaraby.co.uk/|access-date=20 February 2022|archive-date=20 February 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220220112313/https://english.alaraby.co.uk/news/fm-quartet-slams-israel-settlement-expansion-evictions|url-status=live}}</ref>

On 22 September 2022, the group met with Josep Borrell, High Representative of the European Union for Foreign Affairs and Security Policy, and the United Nations Special Coordinator for the Middle East Peace Process, Tor Wennesland, and in a statement said "with a view to advancing the Middle East Peace Process towards a just, comprehensive and lasting peace on the basis of the two-state solution".<ref name = "Sep22">{{cite web|title=Foreign ministers of Egypt, France, Germany and Jordan reiterate commitment to a just peace in the Middle East|url=https://english.wafa.ps/Pages/Details/130958|publisher=WAFA|date=22 September 2022|access-date=25 September 2022|archive-date=26 September 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220926193705/https://english.wafa.ps/Pages/Details/130958|url-status=live}}</ref>

===Quartet developments===
{{main|Quartet on the Middle East}}
In July 2016, the Quartet reported:<blockquote>The continuing policy of settlement construction and expansion in the West Bank and East Jerusalem, designation of land for exclusive Israeli use, and denial of Palestinian development, including the recent high rate of demolitions, is steadily eroding the viability of the two-state solution. This raises legitimate questions about Israel's long-term intentions, which are compounded by the statements of some Israeli ministers that there should never be a Palestinian state. In fact, the transfer of greater powers and responsibilities to Palestinian civil authority...has effectively been stopped.</blockquote> It was within this context that the United Nations passed [[United Nations Security Council Resolution 2334|Security Council Resolution 2334]] in December 2016 in another bid to address the settlement question.<ref name="BayatHerrera2021">{{cite book|author1=Shahram Akbarzadeh|author2=Kylie Baxter|title=Middle East Politics and International Relations|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=K2NgDwAAQBAJ|date=13 June 2018|publisher=Taylor & Francis|isbn=978-1-351-67715-8|pages=77–78}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Report of the Middle East Quartet|url=https://www.un.org/unispal/document/auto-insert-181686/|publisher=United Nations|date=1 July 2016|access-date=25 March 2021|archive-date=24 March 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210324171839/https://www.un.org/unispal/document/auto-insert-181686/|url-status=live}}</ref> The report was significantly altered to appease Israel and as well as urging Israel to stop its settlement policy, urged Palestine to end incitement to violence.<ref>{{cite web|title=Israel/Palestine: Parameters for a Two-State Settlement|url=https://www.crisisgroup.org/middle-east-north-africa/eastern-mediterranean/israelpalestine/israel-palestine-parameters-two-state-settlement|publisher=International Crisis Group|date=28 November 2016|access-date=25 March 2021|archive-date=21 March 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210321193950/https://www.crisisgroup.org/middle-east-north-africa/eastern-mediterranean/israelpalestine/israel-palestine-parameters-two-state-settlement|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Diplomatic Quartet releases report on advancing two-state solution to Israel-Palestine conflict|url=https://news.un.org/en/story/2016/07/533632-diplomatic-quartet-releases-report-advancing-two-state-solution-israel|publisher=United Nations|date=1 July 2016|access-date=25 March 2021|archive-date=18 April 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210418193155/https://news.un.org/en/story/2016/07/533632-diplomatic-quartet-releases-report-advancing-two-state-solution-israel|url-status=live}}</ref>

In a speech to the UN General Assembly in September 2018, Mahmoud Abbas called Donald Trump's policies towards Palestinians an "assault on international law". He said the US is "too biased towards Israel", indicating that others could broker talks and that the US could participate as a member of the Middle East peace Quartet.<ref>{{cite news|title=Rejecting Trump, Abbas at UN says US is too biased to mediate peace talks|url=https://www.timesofisrael.com/rejecting-trump-abbas-at-un-says-us-too-biased-to-mediate-talks-with-israel/|date=27 September 2018|access-date=18 September 2020|archive-date=30 September 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200930224910/https://www.timesofisrael.com/rejecting-trump-abbas-at-un-says-us-too-biased-to-mediate-talks-with-israel/|url-status=live}}</ref> Abbas reiterated this position at a UN Security Council meeting on 11 February 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.securitycouncilreport.org/atf/cf/%7B65BFCF9B-6D27-4E9C-8CD3-CF6E4FF96FF9%7D/S_PV.8717.pdf|title=Security Council Report|access-date=25 September 2020|archive-date=22 January 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210122045504/https://www.securitycouncilreport.org/atf/cf/%7B65BFCF9B-6D27-4E9C-8CD3-CF6E4FF96FF9%7D/S_PV.8717.pdf|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name = "newQ">{{cite news|title=A New 'Quartet' for Israeli-Palestinian Peace|url=https://www.usip.org/publications/2020/07/new-quartet-israeli-palestinian-peace|date=20 July 2020|access-date=18 September 2020|archive-date=27 September 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200927084310/https://www.usip.org/publications/2020/07/new-quartet-israeli-palestinian-peace|url-status=dead}}</ref>

As of 16 September 2020, the UN has not been able to gather the consensus necessary for the Quartet or a group of countries linked to the Quartet to meet.<ref>{{cite news|title=UN unable to convene Quartet to discuss annexation|url=https://www.middleeastmonitor.com/20200627-un-unable-to-convene-quartet-to-discuss-annexation/|publisher=MEMO|date=27 June 2020|access-date=25 September 2020|archive-date=29 September 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200929022110/https://www.middleeastmonitor.com/20200627-un-unable-to-convene-quartet-to-discuss-annexation/|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Abraham Accord, Quartet – Press Conference by Secretary-General António Guterres at UN Headquarters (SG/SM/20258) (Excerpts)|url=https://www.un.org/unispal/document/abraham-accord-quartet-press-conference-by-secretary-general-antonio-guterres-at-un-headquarters-sg-sm-20258-excerpts/|publisher=United Nations|date=25 September 2020|access-date=25 September 2020|archive-date=10 October 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201010030546/https://www.un.org/unispal/document/abraham-accord-quartet-press-conference-by-secretary-general-antonio-guterres-at-un-headquarters-sg-sm-20258-excerpts/|url-status=live}}</ref> On 25 September 2020, at the UN, Abbas called for an international conference early in 2021 to "launch a genuine peace process".<ref>{{cite news|title=Palestinian leader calls for new peace process in UN speech|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/middle_east/palestinian-leader-calls-for-new-peace-process-in-un-speech/2020/09/25/57ce234a-ff44-11ea-b0e4-350e4e60cc91_story.html|publisher=WAPO|date=25 September 2020|access-date=25 September 2020|archive-date=27 September 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200927093101/https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/middle_east/palestinian-leader-calls-for-new-peace-process-in-un-speech/2020/09/25/57ce234a-ff44-11ea-b0e4-350e4e60cc91_story.html|url-status=live}}</ref>

On 15 February 2021, the quartet envoys met virtually and agreed to meet regularly to continue their engagement.<ref>{{cite news|title=A New Tune From The Middle East Quartet – OpEd|url=https://www.eurasiareview.com/26022021-a-new-tune-from-the-middle-east-quartet-oped/|publisher=Eurasia review|date=26 February 2021|access-date=24 March 2021|archive-date=28 February 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210228081124/https://www.eurasiareview.com/26022021-a-new-tune-from-the-middle-east-quartet-oped/|url-status=live}}</ref> On 23 March 2021, the Quartet discussed the reviving of "meaningful negotiations" between Israel and the Palestinians who both need "to refrain from unilateral actions that make a two-state solution more difficult to achieve".<ref>{{cite news|title=Mideast Quartet Discusses Reviving 'Meaningful' Israel, Palestinian Peace Talks|url=https://www.haaretz.com/israel-news/mideast-quartet-discusses-reviving-meaningful-israel-palestinian-peace-talks-1.9648747|work=Haaretz|date=24 March 2021|access-date=24 March 2021|archive-date=23 March 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210323235640/https://www.haaretz.com/israel-news/mideast-quartet-discusses-reviving-meaningful-israel-palestinian-peace-talks-1.9648747|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Statement by the Middle East Quartet Envoys|url=https://unsco.unmissions.org/statement-middle-east-quartet-envoys|publisher=UNSCO|date=23 March 2021|access-date=24 March 2021|archive-date=26 March 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210326185359/https://unsco.unmissions.org/statement-middle-east-quartet-envoys|url-status=live}}</ref>

